allReviews.text: Well deserved map of the week! Brilliant. The environment is amazing, the lighting incredible and fantastic music interpretation and use of patterns throughout. A must play!

The time has come, symphonic. I'm finally reviewing a map of yours. BRACE YOURSELF!!

But before I get into the mapping, I absolutely need to comment on how well done the environments are and how amazing the storytelling in the song is. The first word that comes to mind when experiencing this is "magical". Elecast, I'm sure you've already been told this plenty, but what the hell, this is MAGNIFICENT!! Had me smiling like an idiot!

Getting into the actual mapping, I played both the Expert+ and Hard difficulties. I normally only play the Ex+, but I do have a (maybe weird) reasoning for this.
When I played Ex+, if I'm being *brutally honest*, I came out of it very... mixed. While I think sym plays around with some fun pattern ideas in the highest diff, I think the biggest thing I noticed was *very inconsistent emphasis and representation*. What I mean by this is that the map seems to at random points switch focus from the instrumentals to the vocals, and it was really distracting and hard for me to get a grasp on what the map was trying to **be** in the first place. There were definitely some angles that were hard to read as they weren't indicated as good as they could have been, and it made it difficult for me to invest myself and get lost in this quite frankly beautiful song and experience. 
***HOWEVER.***
It did not sit right with me to come out of this map feeling sour. A lot of what I thought sym was trying to represent gave me thoughts of how it might work better in a lower difficulty, so I decided to then immediately try the Hard, and *bang*, I was right on the money. I REALLY liked the Hard difficulty; it felt like everything was far more consistent, there's this little pattern (0:53) that I thought was super cute and fun, and pretty much erased the complaints I had with Ex+, so my recommendation for my personal optimal experience of this map would be the Hard difficulty. I don't really like pirates.

However, this song has so much energy to it, it's hard not to get enthusiastic listening to it. So I really like the song, especially for a Beat Saber map.

But for me, and seemingly against what most other reviewers feel, this map didn't live up to the song.

Is it a good map? Absolutely. Is it fun to play? Absolutely. Does it have competent representation and gameplay? Absolutely.

But it just... it doesn't capture the energy of the song well enough. A lot of it is too linear and samey for what this song is, and especially coming from Bytrius I would have expected a more memorable map.

Now, I'm going to be honest, I was doubting between positive and neutral, but since the map has so many positive reviews already and most of what I have to say is "not so great", I went with neutral. But honestly compared to 19 out of 20 maps out there this map is great. I just think the song had space for a lot more.

Very fun mapping from Byte with a lot of personality that fits the song nicely! Good representation throughout, I enjoyed the bursts the most I think. The lightshow is pretty insane but I enjoyed playing with it. I think it's better experienced on its own so it can be fully appreciated, but its flashy nature complements the intense parts well with the mapping too, so both ways of experiencing it have their merits. Nice job to both of you, a well-deserved map of the week!

The lights are also extremely cool, but in my case I found them to be too harsh while playing. I missed blocks due to visual overload in a few spots and some of the harder to read mapping was made even harder due to the lighting. I would really enjoy watching this light show on its own, but it did negatively impact my playing experience personally.

Well crafted and enjoyable map set. I can quite easily get headaches when turning lights on for beatsaber, however no such problems here on my playthrough of ex+, and the lights complement the mapping nicely.

Huge props to Byte for the really engaging and fun mapping as always. Simple, yet very well done representation and flow. I liked the funky 90 degree streams towards the end though they felt ever so slightly inconsistent at times. The sway back and forth, and side to side patterning really suits the song and the rhythm choices in most places felt really nice to play and fit the music.

Overall would very much recommend this map set.

[EDIT}: Had no intention to cause strong discourse or drama over this but these things easily come off worse than ones intentions for various reasons.
Heard timings were fixed and i'll just take their word on it and will omit that part of this review.
Own experience was what it was and negative reviews are not trying to tell others not to enjoy their experiences or invalidate their feelings towards a map.
Opinions are just that; opinions.
Lighting alone won't keep this review as negative and trust players will know their own sensitivity to lighting and own safety but as my own was compromised heavily, i wouldn't say the experience was positive either.

Lighting is very subjective but when motion sickness and migraine (yeah thanks for that) come from it this heavily...
Sure wish that safety and playability would be a huge concern in it but this throws all that out the window.

Just my opinion. Others shall make their own.
But i personally can't and wouldn't recommend this to anyone.

This song's album art and, correspondingly, this map's environment, are both based around Mario Kart's mainstay course Rainbow Road, which just adds to my enjoyment of an already fantastic map. Everything about this map is incredibly satisfying in both the mapping and the lightshow. Phoenix's diffs already can be quite challenging, so I am looking forward to trying the guest diffs as well at a later time. Spinvvy's I'm pretty sure I can handle, but we'll see if I can get past even 30 seconds of whatever evil GalaxyMaster has cooked up.

I also have a couple gripes with this, but even then I undoubtedly feel very positive about the map.

I tried to play GalaxyMaster's difficulty but it's absolutely beyond my league. One day. Rest is about Phoenix's top diff. Might try Spinvvy's diff some day.

One that I haven't seen anybody mention is that the custom environment for some reason kinda looks like it's slanted upwards. I think it's because of the placement of the scores. This made me super confused and my first play of the map I had lots of misses because I couldn't judge distance properly. I played it again with environment override and that felt way better.

And yeah, I think the wrist roll chains, while they can work, are a bit abused in this map. Some of them are not really setup properly and they just feel incredibly forceful and shitmissy.

Also, Phoenix, we all know you love windows, but some windows in this map really felt "too inverted", to the point where I missed quite a few of the first notes of the windows because my hand just wasn't in a position to hit them properly.

Other than that, though, this map is really, really good. And there is a lot of good to talk about. I'm going to pick the variety to pinpoint. This map has a lot of variety in pattern styles, speed, difficulty, intensity of hits, usage of bombs, different types of hits... and most of it (except for the above) work really well and add to the representation. While Phoenix maps are generally quite good, they do tend to fall into a certain familiar pattern of alternating leans, windows and certain types of movement. This one has a lot of that, but also has a lot of stuff that's beyond that.

__Great fun aross techy X+ to accable Easy diffs__

I wasn't sure about this one when I listened to the music, but gave it a try because the x+ was under 4nps and I enjoy Shad mapping & lights.
The mapping stands on its own. As does the lightshow. Put them together and you have an excellent map.

For me, one great thing about tech maps is that the fun in the challenge of reading & playing them is not always indicated by the nps. There are some amazing tech maps that are in the 3 to 5 nps range and are a blast to play for me, even if I can't pass the top diffs.
This is one of the best on the lower end of the nps range. The X+ is a solid diff with fun and expressive patterns that kept me smiling all the way through. The lowers are all excellent downmaps with the difficulty progression well reflected in simplified patterns. The Easy is a good acc map for us players who have not broken into the 4 digits of rank yet, but could have had a little more horizontal play in it.
I did find a few of the mapping choices for vocals in the lowers just a but tricky and swung early or late, but that's a skill issue that is a fair challenge for us casual players.

Thank you for another delightful map, Shad.

__Needs more work__

Rewording the review:
Map has potential but suffers from some objective issues that make enjoying the map currently hard for me.
Largest problem being timings being off ranging anywhere between 20-80ms during most of the map and depending on the sections due to offset being wrong in the first place and mistaking 1/3 division rhythms to 1/4 or vice versa.
Vocal sections suffer from this the most but admittedly vocals can be extremely hard to time for many.

Patterns are creative even if some angles can feel a bit odd. eg. up notes before walls & unintuitive feeling follow-up angles on some hits.

Although i respect the attempt put into manual lighting it also gets it's own set of criticism.

I'll bring all the issues up personally with the mapper in further detail.
